<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<beans xmlns="http://www.springframework.org/schema/beans"
       xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"
       xsi:schemaLocation="
        http://www.springframework.org/schema/beans http://www.springframework.org/schema/beans/spring-beans.xsd">

    <!-- bean definitions here -->

    <!--  <bean id = "alien" class = "org.Spring.Alien" scope = "prototype"> </bean> -->
    <bean id = "alien" class = "org.Spring.Alien" autowire="byType" >
        <!-- ASSIGNING AGE VIA A PROPERTY TAG -->
       <!-- <property name = "age" value = "21"> </property>    -->
        <!-- This will assign value of 21 to age by default (Spring ki taraf se)
            Due to this, we don't need to use this obj.setAge(21);-->


        <!-- ASSIGNING AGE VIA A CONSTRUCTOR -->
        <!-- <constructor-arg value = "21"/> -->             <!-- This is for single parameter constructors -->

        <!-- FOR MULTI PARAMETERISED CONSTRUCTORS, WE ISE INDEXES TO DENOTE THE ORDER OF EXECUTION -->
        <!--   <constructor-arg index = "0" value = "21"/>   -->
          <!-- <constructor-arg index = "1" ref = "lap1"/>   -->

        <!-- CONCEPT OF AUTOWITRING -->
        <property name = "age" value = "21" />
        <!--  <property name = "com" ref = "lap1"/>  -->


            <!--  <property name = "laptop1" ref = "lap1">   </property>  -->
        <!-- Spring laptop bean ka object khud create karke Alien ke andar inject karega
          Isliye hume manually new Laptop() ya obj.setLaptop() likhne ki zarurat nahi -->
    </bean>

    <bean id = "lap1"  class = "org.Spring.Laptop"  >  <!-- This creates laptop object on its own -->

    </bean>

    <bean id = "com" class = "org.Spring.Desktop"  primary = "true" >  <!-- This creates desktop object on its own -->

    </bean>



</beans>


<!-- SEARCH FOR spring 6 bean documentation xml ON google to get this bean tag-->

        <!-- Bean scope defines how many objects Spring creates and when -->
        <!-- singleton (default): one object per container, created at startup -->
        <!-- prototype: new object created every time getBean() is called -->
        <!-- Scope is controlled using the 'scope' attribute in the bean tag -->

        <!--

        // <property> is used to inject values or object references into a bean (Setter Injection)
        // 'value' injects primitive or String data, 'ref' injects another bean
        // Spring creates all required objects and calls setter methods automatically
        // This removes object creation logic from classes and enables Dependency Injection

        // 'lap1' is the bean ID used by Spring to identify the Laptop object in the container
        // <property ref="lap1"> tells Spring which object to inject
        // The variable name (laptop1) and bean ID (lap1) are independent
        // Spring resolves the reference and injects the object automatically


        // Autowire lets Spring automatically choose which dependency to inject
        // It works based on type, name, or constructor matching
        // If a property has an explicit 'ref', autowiring is skipped for that property
        // Explicit dependency injection always overrides autowire
        // ⚠️ byType works ONLY when there is ONE bean of that type
        If there are multiple Laptop beans → Spring gets confused → exception.
        The Solution to this confusion is the use of Primary Bean
        // primary is used to resolve ambiguity when multiple beans of the same type exist
        // During autowire byType, Spring injects the bean marked as primary
        // primary works only when Spring is auto-selecting a dependency
        // Explicit <property ref="..."> always overrides the primary bean


        FINAL OUTPUT : (AUTOWIRE -> byType, primary bean is desktop)
        21
        Object Created...
        Compiling using Desktop..

        Also, if you dont want to create objects of each bean explicitly, use lazy-init = "true" , to
        ensure that object of that bean hasn't been created explicitly.
        Jis bean ka object nahi chahiye, us bean ke end me lazy-init = "true" add karo.





        -->
